    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Pleopeltis accedens improperly include experiencing nausea due to its toxic compounds, such as caesalpinian glycosides, which can cause gastrointestinal distress. Additionally, improper use may lead to severe allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis, due to the plant's allergenic properties. Suffering liver damage is also a possibility due to the hepatotoxic effects of certain compounds found in Pleopeltis accedens, such as sesquiterpenes. Furthermore, improper handling can result in skin irritation, including dermatitis and rashes, caused by the plant's sap or other irritating compounds. If ingested in large quantities, Pleopeltis accedens can cause respiratory depression, a potentially life-threatening condition, due to its sedative and depressant effects on the central nervous system.",
    "uses": "Pleopeltis accedens, also known as the tropical polypody, has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. Its leaves have been applied topically to treat wounds, burns, and skin irritations due to its anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties. In some regions, it is used to treat fever, cough, and respiratory issues. The plant is also believed to have antioxidant and immunomodulatory effects, making it potentially useful in cancer treatment and immune system support. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal potential of Pleopeltis accedens.",
    "taxonomy": "Pleopeltis accedens is classified within the family Polypodiaceae, which is a group of vascular plants commonly known as polypody ferns. The species is a member of the genus Pleopeltis, which is a genus of epiphytic and terrestrial ferns. Pleopeltis accedens is also part of the order Polypodiales, a group of ferns that are characterized by their pinnate or bipinnate leaves. At the kingdom level, Pleopeltis accedens is classified as Plantae, which includes all plants. Additionally, at the rank of division, it belongs to the division Pteridophyta, which is the group that contains all ferns.",
    "benefits": "Pleopeltis accedens is known to have various health benefits, particularly in traditional medicine. The plant is used to treat a range of conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and skin problems. Its extracts have been shown to exhibit anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may contribute to its therapeutic effects. Additionally, Pleopeltis accedens is believed to have antimicrobial properties, making it a potential treatment for infections. Further research is needed to fully understand the plant's potential health benefits and its effects on human health.",
    "parts": "Pleopeltis accedens is a species of epiphytic fern. However, information about the medicinal parts of Pleopeltis accedens is limited, but it is known to be used in traditional medicine. The rhizome of the plant is sometimes used in folk medicine for its potential therapeutic properties. More research is needed to fully understand its medicinal uses. Further study of the plant's parts and their properties could lead to the discovery of new medicinal applications.",
    "intro": "Pleopeltis accedens, also known as the Antillean polypody, is a species of epiphytic fern native to the tropical regions of Central and South America. This plant has been traditionally used in folk medicine for its various health benefits, including the treatment of wounds, inflammation, and respiratory issues, due to its antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. The bioactive constituents of Pleopeltis accedens include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and sesquiterpenes, which contribute to its medicinal properties. The most common herbal preparations made with Pleopeltis accedens include infusions, decoctions, and extracts, which are often used to treat various health conditions and promote overall well-being."
